00:23.941 --> 00:27.361
I'm thinking we'll go do the show,
and then we'll go get...

00:27.444 --> 00:29.088
If you want to do a slice,
we'll get a slice.

00:29.112 --> 00:32.156
- I'll do a slice if I can get a fountain...
- Let's go in here.

00:32.241 --> 00:35.285
Do they have fountain soda?
'Cause I don't like cans.

00:35.786 --> 00:37.496
Yeah, this is it.

00:37.579 --> 00:39.039
- I love it, yeah.
- Yeah, right.

00:39.957 --> 00:43.460
But my point is, if I got an indoor
ball... a woman's ball...

00:43.919 --> 00:46.213
and I was at the top of the key,
I'd sink more threes.

00:46.296 --> 00:49.716
Yeah, but we're not allowed
at that Y anymore.

00:49.800 --> 00:51.677
No, but I'm saying if...

00:51.760 --> 00:55.973
Look, you don't have... You can go
in disguises to any place you want,

00:56.056 --> 00:58.350
if you know what you're doing
on the hard court.

00:58.850 --> 01:01.019
- I'm nervous about tonight.
- Why?

01:01.103 --> 01:03.438
'Cause we're filming it for the TV thing.

01:03.522 --> 01:05.566
I don't care. I'm gonna get high before...

01:06.692 --> 01:09.778
<i>♪ Tonight when I chase the Dragon ♪</i>

01:13.740 --> 01:15.158
- It's show time!
- It's show time!

01:17.327 --> 01:20.831
[announcer] <i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>
<i>welcome to the Lyceum Theater.</i>

01:20.914 --> 01:22.624
<i>Unfortunately at this performance,</i>

01:22.708 --> 01:25.419
<i>the roles of Gil Faizon
and George St. Geegland</i>

01:25.502 --> 01:29.047
<i>will be played by Gil Faizon
and George St. Geegland.</i>

01:29.923 --> 01:31.466
Let's do Broadway.

01:32.801 --> 01:34.261
I'll see you after the show.

01:35.012 --> 01:36.513
So fucking dumb.

01:39.516 --> 01:44.813
<i>And now, please welcome,
Gil Faizon and George St. Geegland.</i>

01:46.189 --> 01:49.151
[applause]

01:59.953 --> 02:01.413
Oh, hey! I know you.

02:02.873 --> 02:06.335
[both] Oh, hello.

02:06.710 --> 02:10.339
- Charmed I'm sure, I'm Gil Faizon
- And I am George St. Geegland.

02:10.422 --> 02:12.466
And we are two legendary bachelors

02:12.549 --> 02:14.718
who live on the
Upper West Side of Manhattan.

02:14.801 --> 02:18.221
Which is the coffee breath
of neighborhoods.

02:18.555 --> 02:21.892
We want to give a shout-out
to the mezzanine and the balcony!

02:22.017 --> 02:23.685
[applause]

02:26.813 --> 02:30.984
You guys are the reason we do this show!

02:31.318 --> 02:35.197
But we will be making eye contact
solely with the orchestra.

02:35.947 --> 02:38.992
We are gonna have so much fun tonight

02:39.076 --> 02:42.871
because theater is the hot,
new thing right now.

02:42.954 --> 02:47.000
There's <i>Hamilton </i> and no other examples.

02:48.043 --> 02:49.836
Now, speaking of theater being hot,

02:49.920 --> 02:52.547
you'll notice that we are filming
the show tonight.

02:52.631 --> 02:55.509
Yes. You see cameras all over the place.

02:56.301 --> 03:01.723
We're filming this as a special
for Investigation Discovery.

03:02.682 --> 03:04.309
No, it's for Netflix.

03:04.393 --> 03:05.560
It's a binge-watch.

03:05.644 --> 03:09.189
It's a binge-watch. You watch an episode
of a show, then you wait a week,

03:09.272 --> 03:11.983
and then you binge-watch another episode.

03:12.067 --> 03:14.236
Also, if you see a camera,

03:14.319 --> 03:18.198
you know, look right down
the barrel of the lens, all right?

03:18.281 --> 03:22.786
And you know, we're trying to convey
that we have a diverse audience,

03:22.869 --> 03:26.039
so if you're white, tonight,
if you could just not be.

03:26.164 --> 03:27.207
Yeah!

03:27.290 --> 03:28.291
[audience laugh]

03:28.708 --> 03:30.502
All right, that covers the business.

03:30.585 --> 03:33.922
We want to also give a shout-out
to our dear intern Ravi in the booth.

03:34.005 --> 03:36.550
Shout-out to Ravi!

03:38.218 --> 03:39.469
OK. This is Ravi.

03:39.553 --> 03:43.056
Ravi is a junior at the
NYU Tisch School for the Arts.

03:43.140 --> 03:45.350
Yes, he's studying to be a playwright,

03:45.434 --> 03:49.271
so he's doing tech for us,
unpaid, for nine months.

03:49.479 --> 03:53.066
Yeah. He's Ravi Nandan, OK?

03:53.150 --> 03:56.111
He's one of these new Indian types.

03:56.194 --> 03:58.488
He's a real "Aziz, I'm sorry."

03:58.572 --> 03:59.823
[audience laugh]

03:59.906 --> 04:04.369
But we like to joke that Ravi
is the master of <i>fun.</i>

04:08.957 --> 04:11.334
One of our famous turns.

04:12.335 --> 04:13.712
Back to us.

04:13.795 --> 04:15.505
Some of our accolades:

04:15.589 --> 04:20.677
We are the recipients
of a 1997 restraining order.

04:21.386 --> 04:26.016
Keeping us 100 feet at all times
from America's greatest actor,

04:26.099 --> 04:27.768
Mr. Alan Alda.

04:28.435 --> 04:33.106
Alan Alda, double A, beep, beep!
"Get off my property!"

04:33.690 --> 04:35.817
But who are we really? You know?

04:35.901 --> 04:38.737
What is our essence? How to describe?

04:38.820 --> 04:42.199
You know when you get to the bottom
of a tub of hummus.

04:43.074 --> 04:45.243
And you can't fit your carrot in there,

04:45.327 --> 04:47.704
so you gotta use your fingies
to scoop it out?

04:48.997 --> 04:51.166
Bam! That's us, baby!

04:51.249 --> 04:52.918
[applause]

04:53.835 --> 04:57.339
How can I describe
the kind of vibe we give off?

04:57.422 --> 05:00.383
You know when you walk by a travel agency

05:00.467 --> 05:02.135
and you're like, "What?"

05:04.387 --> 05:05.722
- There you go.
- Yeah.

05:07.057 --> 05:10.060
We are the <i>Yerba Mate </i> tea bags,

05:10.143 --> 05:13.188
steaming the counter top
of American pop culture.

05:13.814 --> 05:15.816
But who are we as individuals?

05:15.899 --> 05:17.901
Do you mind if I get into my big story?

05:17.984 --> 05:19.653
See the stage, use it.

05:19.736 --> 05:21.780
And I accept the stage from you, sir.

05:22.155 --> 05:25.200
Of course, you all know me,
I'm George St. Geegland.

05:25.325 --> 05:26.368
- [crowd hooting]
- Hush.

05:27.786 --> 05:30.372
I'm the type of man
you would catch at a party

05:30.455 --> 05:32.249
going through the coats.

05:33.708 --> 05:35.877
I am neither Jewish, nor a woman,

05:35.961 --> 05:38.713
but like many men over the age of 70,

05:38.797 --> 05:42.384
I have reached that point in life
where I am somehow both.

05:43.718 --> 05:45.804
I was born in Providence, Rhode Island,

05:45.887 --> 05:50.267
and I am responsible for reintroducing
the Polio virus to my school district.

05:51.226 --> 05:55.146
As a novelist,
I was once compared to Philip Roth.

05:55.230 --> 05:58.024
I was also once compared
to a police sketch

05:58.108 --> 06:00.360
of this Central Park flasher.

06:01.069 --> 06:05.323
And guess what, ladies and gentlemen,
I've been married three times.

06:05.407 --> 06:07.200
Unlucky in love, we like to joke.

06:07.284 --> 06:09.828
Wonderful! Wonderful! Wonderful!

06:10.537 --> 06:16.209
All three of my wives died in the same way
on the same staircase.

06:18.545 --> 06:23.883
Each death learning from
and improving upon the death before it.

06:24.926 --> 06:27.596
And a fun fact
for this evening's performance,

06:27.679 --> 06:30.515
I am on competing medications.

06:33.685 --> 06:35.312
[applause]

06:39.524 --> 06:41.860
Well, charmed I'm sure, I'm Gil Faizon.

06:41.943 --> 06:46.323
I am a Tony Award viewing actor.

06:46.990 --> 06:49.117
And whether I live
in your building or not,

06:49.200 --> 06:52.245
I am somehow on your co-op board.

06:53.580 --> 06:57.500
I look like if Steven Spielberg
hadn't made any money.

06:57.584 --> 06:59.127
[audience laugh]

07:00.587 --> 07:03.089
Over the years,
I've had a real back and forth

07:03.173 --> 07:07.135
a <i>tête-à-têtes </i> of sorts
with fellow actor, Richard Dreyfuss.

07:07.218 --> 07:09.846
He of course got the lead in <i>Jaws,</i>

07:09.930 --> 07:13.308
and I have lockjaw
from all the cocaine I've done.

07:15.518 --> 07:18.271
I'm also an unlicensed doula.

07:21.316 --> 07:24.611
But I've made the most of my living
as a voice-over artist.

07:24.986 --> 07:28.531
I was very nearly
the official voice of CBS.

07:28.615 --> 07:31.534
Yes he was... I'm sorry,
I did not mean to interrupt you,

07:31.618 --> 07:34.496
but you did such
a beautiful audition for CBS.

07:34.579 --> 07:36.915
Would you do for them tonight
your CBS audition?

07:36.998 --> 07:39.167
I don't know if the audience
wants to hear it.

07:39.250 --> 07:40.919
[applause]

07:42.504 --> 07:45.340
I was gonna do it regardless, you know.

07:46.049 --> 07:48.677
This was my audition for CBS.

07:48.760 --> 07:50.637
[clears throat]

07:52.472 --> 07:57.143
Charmed, I'm sure, this is Gil Faizon
represented by Don Buchwald & Associates.

07:57.811 --> 08:00.605
Reading for the role of CBS.

08:01.272 --> 08:05.568
This is CBS, baby!

08:06.027 --> 08:07.445
Fun and flirty,

08:07.529 --> 08:10.949
but am I nuts, did you do
like a second alternate take?

08:11.032 --> 08:12.575
- Yeah.
- Right, you did.

08:12.659 --> 08:16.079
As an actor, you got to give options, OK?

08:16.162 --> 08:20.041
This is one of the main things
that I teach in my acting seminar,

08:20.125 --> 08:23.586
which is called,
"Improvisation for Non-Listeners."

08:24.379 --> 08:28.508
It's a five-hour seminar,
and you get a chicken lunch.

08:28.591 --> 08:30.135
It's a buffalo chicken wrap.

08:30.218 --> 08:33.513
- It's so cold...
- It's 90 percent romaine lettuce.

08:33.596 --> 08:37.017
It's a cold wrap, a warm Sierra Mist,

08:37.100 --> 08:41.104
- it's on a Saturday, it's 900 dollars.
- Yeah...

08:41.855 --> 08:44.649
It really is, it really is, OK.

08:44.983 --> 08:48.611
This is take two,
Gil Faizon, charmed, I'm sure,

08:48.695 --> 08:52.032
formerly represented
by Don Buchwald and Associates,

08:52.115 --> 08:53.616
reading for the role of CBS.

08:55.910 --> 08:57.370
CBS?

08:57.454 --> 08:58.788
[high pitched] All right!

08:59.080 --> 09:00.081
Perfect!

09:00.290 --> 09:02.500
Perfect! And let me say something,

09:02.584 --> 09:07.255
I am like, Raven-Symoné level upset
that you did not get that job.

09:07.338 --> 09:10.884
George, That is so Raven of you to say.

09:10.967 --> 09:13.303
It's not ravin', it's true.

09:13.386 --> 09:16.056
You, Gil Faizon,
how many times have I told you?

09:16.139 --> 09:18.183
You are the strongest actor in New York?

09:18.266 --> 09:19.350
Ah, this guy...

09:19.434 --> 09:20.977
This guy is my rock.

09:21.061 --> 09:25.648
He was the one who broke the news to me
that I wasn't gonna get the CBS job.

09:25.732 --> 09:28.127
- Who knows? Who knows? Who knows?
- [high pitched] Yeah, yeah, yeah.

09:28.151 --> 09:29.194
And you know what?

09:29.277 --> 09:32.655
He wouldn't let me sulk
for one single second, nay, nay, nay.

09:32.739 --> 09:35.075
He made me go right back on the horse.

09:35.158 --> 09:37.702
We started doing heroin that afternoon.

09:38.203 --> 09:42.832
And we'd shoot it between our toes
to keep our arms clear for racquetball.

09:42.999 --> 09:44.000
Yeah.

09:44.084 --> 09:45.627
And then what did he do?

09:45.710 --> 09:49.172
He gave me the greatest gift
that a writer can give an actor.

09:49.255 --> 09:51.883
He wrote a play for <i>me </i> to star in.

09:51.966 --> 09:53.760
Which brings us to tonight.

09:53.843 --> 09:57.180
You see, over the years, I've written
several plays for Gil and I to perform...

09:57.263 --> 09:59.849
- George, you remember the first?
- The first play we ever did?

09:59.933 --> 10:01.392
- Yes.
- Yes. I'll never forget it.

10:01.476 --> 10:04.270
The first play we ever did?
I'll never forget.

10:05.021 --> 10:09.317
I was inspired by
and directly stolen from...

10:10.318 --> 10:12.737
Sam Shepard's classic, <i>True West.</i>

10:13.154 --> 10:16.032
Yeah, but ours was called,
<i>True Upper West.</i>

10:17.200 --> 10:21.162
That was the big
M. Night Shyamalan twist at the end.

10:21.246 --> 10:24.916
Is at the end, you'd widen out,
which is hard to do in a play.

10:24.999 --> 10:27.669
But you'd widen out.

10:27.752 --> 10:31.464
And the whole time
it had been the Upper West side,

10:31.548 --> 10:33.967
and there's like, a Judaica store,

10:34.551 --> 10:37.011
that's always closed.

10:38.638 --> 10:39.681
Who's that?

10:39.889 --> 10:41.641
Who's that? Who's that guy?

10:41.724 --> 10:43.560
That's a sewer pop-up guy.

10:43.643 --> 10:46.855
You know, a guy pops out of his sewer,
"No, thanks," back down.

10:47.897 --> 10:52.652
Now, famously in the revival of <i>True West,</i>
you'd see Reilly and...

10:53.987 --> 10:57.198
- I'm sorry. And "Phil Sey" Hoffman.
- [groans]

10:57.574 --> 10:58.741
I'm sorry.

10:58.825 --> 11:04.205
It's hard, because we get choked up on cue
at the same point, every show.

11:04.956 --> 11:09.085
We just really wanted to make
Philip Seymour Hoffman's death about us.

11:09.169 --> 11:10.170
You know?

11:10.628 --> 11:15.425
Ladies and gentlemen, it behooves you
when a famous person dies,

11:15.508 --> 11:18.803
blame the year and make it about you.

11:18.887 --> 11:22.140
- [George] Yeah, yeah.
- [audience clapping]

11:25.768 --> 11:30.940
To take a Getty Image,
a watermarked Getty Image,

11:31.024 --> 11:35.361
and post a picture
on your shitty Facebook.com page.

11:35.737 --> 11:39.407
It means the world to these dead people.

11:40.575 --> 11:44.120
Now, famously,
in that revival of <i>True West,</i>

11:44.203 --> 11:47.123
John C. Reilly and "Phil Sey" Hoffman

11:47.206 --> 11:49.459
would switch parts every night.

11:52.211 --> 11:54.297
We would do <i>our </i> version of that.

11:54.380 --> 11:56.925
We would switch medications, OK?

11:57.967 --> 12:00.094
I would take George's anti-psychotics.

12:00.178 --> 12:02.805
And I would apply Gil's eczema cream.

12:04.057 --> 12:06.768
But many of you millennials
probably know us

12:06.851 --> 12:10.730
from our hit existential drama,
<i>Waiting for Godot...</i>

12:10.813 --> 12:11.898
Hello.

12:12.732 --> 12:16.861
But in our version,
Godot shows up, like three minutes in,

12:18.237 --> 12:21.157
and then we prank that mofo
with <i>Too Much Tuna, </i> baby.

12:22.075 --> 12:24.243
We come out with bowler hats on.

12:24.327 --> 12:25.648
We take them off, [clicks tongue]

12:25.703 --> 12:28.331
we got two tuna sandwiches on our heads.

12:28.414 --> 12:30.750
And the audience was in stitches.

12:30.833 --> 12:35.505
Literally, because we were performing
at a burn ward in Washington Heights.

12:36.464 --> 12:37.882
And these...

12:38.299 --> 12:40.718
- Say it.
- These fucking Dominicans...

12:42.053 --> 12:45.390
It was like...
Hey, shut the door. It was like...

12:45.974 --> 12:47.809
Like they didn't understand it.

12:47.892 --> 12:51.437
And those that understood English,
it was like, they didn't like it.

12:52.271 --> 12:55.316
Most of our plays
had been mounted in hospitals,

12:55.400 --> 12:59.904
or kill shelters
or as a skit during break at AA.

13:00.405 --> 13:04.701
Which is why it is such an honor
to be here tonight.

13:04.784 --> 13:07.453
At the Winter Garden Theater!

13:08.037 --> 13:11.124
No, no, the Lyceum Theater!

13:11.207 --> 13:12.625
[applause]

13:15.169 --> 13:17.755
I thought we booked
the Winter Garden Theater.

13:17.839 --> 13:21.384
Have you fucking tried dealing
with the Shubert Organization?

13:21.759 --> 13:24.095
I mean, this is a historic theater.

13:24.178 --> 13:27.932
Liza Minnelli mounted her iconic
<i>Liza with a "Z" </i> on this very stage,

13:28.016 --> 13:30.268
directed by the great Bob Fosse.

13:30.351 --> 13:32.145
And if you listen very closely,

13:32.228 --> 13:35.440
you can hear in the rafters
the ghost of Bob Fosse,

13:35.523 --> 13:38.276
snorting Dexedrine and drinking Visine.

13:39.861 --> 13:44.532
Here in this theater, haunted by ghosts
who could not book a different theater.

13:46.034 --> 13:49.912
Here in this theater
which is basically on Sixth Avenue.

13:51.164 --> 13:53.833
So many great playwrights
have staged their works.

13:53.916 --> 13:56.753
Tennessee Williams and his sister Serena.

13:58.129 --> 14:01.215
You know, they were rivals
but they loved each other.

14:01.299 --> 14:05.678
- I blame the father.
- [both] He pushed them too hard.

14:06.387 --> 14:08.556
- I like your take.
- I like your style.

14:09.265 --> 14:11.559
That's why this is the perfect venue

14:11.642 --> 14:13.436
for us to present to you...

14:13.519 --> 14:15.438
our new play!

14:15.897 --> 14:17.899
Ravi, curtain!

14:20.401 --> 14:22.862
[cheering]

14:27.992 --> 14:33.456
Can you imagine a Broadway show
exceeding your expectations

14:33.539 --> 14:35.833
by having a set?

14:37.085 --> 14:42.173
All of this stuff cobbled together
from discarded Broadway sets

14:42.256 --> 14:46.803
from some weird warehouse
in Secaucus, New Jersey.

14:47.261 --> 14:49.055
They have everything at this place.

14:49.138 --> 14:51.307
Old props, old costumes,

14:51.391 --> 14:55.353
the cast of <i>Newsies</i>
huddled over a flaming garbage can.

14:56.396 --> 15:01.776
This right here, this is the actual set
from the 2005 revival of <i>Steel Magnolias</i>

15:01.859 --> 15:04.153
mounted right here at the Lyceum Theater.

15:04.237 --> 15:07.407
<i>Steel Magnolias, </i> first a play,
then a movie, then again, a play.

15:07.490 --> 15:10.326
The Broadway equivalent
of moving back in with your parents.

15:11.160 --> 15:15.832
What about this wall and staircase
from a classic work of August Wilson's.

15:15.915 --> 15:19.502
August Wilson, the acclaimed
African-American playwright.

15:19.585 --> 15:22.046
I could name so many titles of his plays,

15:22.130 --> 15:24.048
but I'm gonna walk over here now.

15:25.508 --> 15:28.219
And what's this right here?
A trapdoor, yes.

15:28.302 --> 15:32.515
This is the trapdoor from the set
of <i>The Diary of Anne Frank. </i> Yeah!

15:32.598 --> 15:35.435
Not to be confused
with the diary of Anne Hathaway

15:35.518 --> 15:38.479
which we stole out of her purse
at the Gotham Awards.

15:38.938 --> 15:41.149
And what's inside? Oh, no, what's this?

15:41.232 --> 15:42.733
Oh, me, oh, my!

15:42.817 --> 15:47.780
It's the pillowman
from Martin McDonagh's <i>The Pillowman.</i>

15:47.864 --> 15:51.242
And for those you at the crappy sightline
who can't see this, raise your hand.

15:51.325 --> 15:53.744
Raise your hands if you can't see this.
All right. OK.

15:53.870 --> 15:56.497
So what you're missing is...

15:56.914 --> 16:02.170
It's a pillow with googly eyes
and paper towel arms, all right?

16:02.837 --> 16:06.674
So next time, get your tickets earlier
or just make more money.

16:12.096 --> 16:16.684
And in honor of Jean-Paul Sartre's
classic play, <i>No Exit,</i>

16:16.767 --> 16:20.688
we have installed a "No Exit" sign.

16:21.606 --> 16:27.403
Which the city of New York informs
us is a massive fire hazard.

16:27.820 --> 16:29.864
And what's this right here, the gramophone

16:29.947 --> 16:32.575
and shelving unit
from a Tony Award winning play,

16:32.658 --> 16:36.412
again mounted right here
at the Lyceum Theater, <i>I Am My Own Wife.</i>

16:36.496 --> 16:39.624
You know, I once had Gil
pretend to be my own wife,

16:39.707 --> 16:43.294
in order to throw off
the homicide detective's timeline.

16:44.837 --> 16:47.048
I wore a dress.

16:48.341 --> 16:52.345
Why he wore a dress to make a phone call,
we will never know.

16:53.304 --> 16:56.974
And what's this right here?
This is the heart and soul of this set.

16:57.058 --> 17:00.311
This is the original stoop
from <i>The Cosby Show.</i>

17:00.895 --> 17:03.231
Which we got for like, nothing.

17:04.272 --> 17:06.400
They paid us to take it.

17:06.483 --> 17:10.530
They were like, "This thing's got
bad juju, get it off our hands", you know.

17:10.613 --> 17:14.575
But of course, the final piece
of inanimate set decoration,

17:14.659 --> 17:16.493
is you, the audience.

17:16.577 --> 17:20.455
A collection of comedy nerds
