George, did you know the name Steely Dan

35:29.753 --> 35:32.922
originated as a dildo
in a William Burroughs novel?

35:33.006 --> 35:34.424
Of course, I know that.

35:34.507 --> 35:37.010
You and I know a lot about Steely Dan.

35:40.597 --> 35:41.598
- Gil?
- Here.

35:41.723 --> 35:43.892
- Would you check the mail for me?
- All right.

35:43.975 --> 35:46.519
I'm waiting on a reply from my publisher

35:46.603 --> 35:50.357
about my new novel, <i>Next Stop: Ronkonkoma.</i>

35:50.732 --> 35:53.777
It's the story of a Long Island
railroad trip

35:53.860 --> 35:57.155
told from a hundred
different perspectives.

36:03.036 --> 36:04.537
Let's see here. [clears throat]

36:04.621 --> 36:06.206
"Attention, tenants.

36:06.289 --> 36:10.043
Water will be shut off
from 9 a.m. until 4 p.m.

36:10.126 --> 36:11.795
to punish the unemployed."

36:14.089 --> 36:15.674
Seems mean-spirited, right?

36:15.757 --> 36:17.467
I make my own water.

36:20.220 --> 36:21.680
Oh, yeah, OK. This one.

36:21.763 --> 36:24.391
"Dear Mr. Reddington and Mr. Stone,

36:24.474 --> 36:28.645
Your rent controlled apartment
is no longer rent-controlled."

36:30.730 --> 36:33.942
But we've been living
in this apartment for 40 years,

36:34.025 --> 36:36.486
paying $75 a month.

36:36.903 --> 36:39.698
It's our God-given right
to pay the same amount of rent

36:39.781 --> 36:42.409
regardless of property value or inflation.

36:42.742 --> 36:44.536
This is an outrage.

36:44.953 --> 36:46.996
Ravi, I need that chair to shatter.

36:47.080 --> 36:48.748
Let me see this.

36:48.832 --> 36:52.585
"Your rent is being increased
to $2,500 a month."

36:52.961 --> 36:56.131
Twenty-five hundred dollars
for a measly five-bedroom

36:56.214 --> 36:58.675
with office, crown molding, and fireplace?

36:59.175 --> 37:01.219
How much money do I even have on me?

37:01.302 --> 37:04.431
What is this?
"Remember, you have Alzheimer's."

37:04.514 --> 37:06.599
What does that even mean?

37:08.059 --> 37:12.272
I'm so sick of finding
all these stupid notes in all my shit.

37:14.399 --> 37:16.776
When I find the guy
that's putting them there...

37:16.860 --> 37:18.987
What are you gonna do to him, Georgie?

37:19.070 --> 37:20.947
You know, c'mere jabroni.

37:21.030 --> 37:22.449
Stay out of my mirror.

37:22.574 --> 37:25.326
[Gil] Yeah, yeah, yeah.

37:25.827 --> 37:28.037
Tell me, Gil, is there a third...

37:30.081 --> 37:33.334
Tell me, Gil,
is there a third letter from my...

37:34.043 --> 37:35.962
- It works best if I do the set up.
- OK.

37:39.507 --> 37:41.801
Gil, is there a... Fucking wait!

37:41.885 --> 37:44.429
[loud laughter]

37:55.815 --> 37:59.694
Say, Gil, is there a third letter
from my publisher?

37:59.778 --> 38:02.030
Maybe if they sent a big enough advance,

38:02.113 --> 38:04.532
we don't have to worry about the new rent.

38:08.453 --> 38:11.164
- Give me the fucking letter.
- Just ask for the letter.

38:12.040 --> 38:14.501
- Are we on the same team?
- Yeah.

38:14.584 --> 38:16.252
The '86 Mets.

38:19.005 --> 38:21.508
- You're all right, you know that?
- Yeah, thanks, man.

38:22.175 --> 38:25.220
- It's from them and it's nice and thin.
- Less is more, Georgie.

38:25.303 --> 38:28.097
Good news comes in thin envelopes.

38:28.932 --> 38:30.558
"Dear Mr. Reddington.

38:30.642 --> 38:34.938
We received your amazing manuscript,
<i>Next Stop: Ronkonkoma.</i>

38:35.021 --> 38:38.525
A one thousand page,
totally unproofed document.

38:39.859 --> 38:44.239
Unfortunately, we are only interested
in young adult puff pieces now.

38:44.322 --> 38:46.533
Like <i>Twilight </i> or <i>The Corrections.</i>

38:47.116 --> 38:50.161
Maybe you should give more thought
to a younger audience."

38:50.829 --> 38:52.372
The nerve of these people.

38:52.455 --> 38:54.499
I think about teens all the time.

38:56.000 --> 38:58.920
But, George, what did the letter say?

39:05.218 --> 39:08.012
It said I'm not gonna get the book deal.

39:08.096 --> 39:09.973
Oh, my God,
I'm not gonna get the book deal.

39:10.640 --> 39:14.352
And I already bought that sheep dog
for the author photo.

39:15.353 --> 39:17.814
Boy, that guy is going back to Chinatown.

39:18.106 --> 39:22.902
[audience groans and laughs]

39:24.112 --> 39:25.488
Strap in, folks.

39:25.697 --> 39:30.702
[laughter and clapping]

39:32.662 --> 39:34.747
What happens if you don't get the advance?

39:34.831 --> 39:37.041
Without that advance,
we don't have any money,

39:37.125 --> 39:38.793
and we're gonna lose our apartment.

39:38.877 --> 39:43.298
But we've been living in this apartment
for 700 Sundays.

39:43.381 --> 39:46.593
[upbeat music plays]

39:46.676 --> 39:49.512
1951, Flatbush Avenue.

39:49.596 --> 39:53.099
I'm five years old and there's two things
in this world that I love.

39:53.182 --> 39:54.601
The Brooklyn Dodgers,

39:54.684 --> 39:58.354
and when my mom pushes my head
in between her big Polish tits.

39:58.438 --> 39:59.856
[ice-cream truck music plays]

39:59.939 --> 40:01.399
The Ice Cream Man is here.

40:01.482 --> 40:05.069
He says I can have a big boy cone
if he can stick a finger in my tushie.

40:06.946 --> 40:10.283
1951, Providence, Rhode Island.

40:10.366 --> 40:14.203
I'm five years old and my mother
is raising me as a girl.

40:15.288 --> 40:18.458
My father is drinking whiskey
in a pitch-black room

40:18.541 --> 40:20.585
and we are not allowed in there.

40:21.085 --> 40:23.087
My big brother Spuddy grabs me.

40:23.171 --> 40:26.716
"Hey, George, you want to go
see a dead body?"

40:27.050 --> 40:29.552
He takes me down to the train tracks,

40:29.636 --> 40:32.263
but I had seen that one already.

40:33.765 --> 40:37.560
Flash forward.
I'm a freshman at Zero Mostel High.

40:38.186 --> 40:42.523
My best friend Lamar challenges me
to drink a whole bottle of canola oil.

40:42.607 --> 40:46.903
I do it, and to this day,
when I burp, popcorn comes out.

40:48.446 --> 40:53.076
Flash forward. I'm a sophomore
at Jonesy School for Misfits.

40:53.159 --> 40:57.163
It's just me and a nun
and a young Robert Durst.

40:58.373 --> 41:03.044
Fun fact: Robert Durst and my mother
jumped off the same roof.

41:03.503 --> 41:06.881
On the one hand,
I was sad my mother killed herself,

41:06.965 --> 41:10.802
but on the other hand,
I was happy it was my birthday.

41:12.679 --> 41:14.389
It's true. He was. He really was.

41:17.225 --> 41:21.980
Flash forward to the oft forgotten
and rarely discussed decade,

41:22.063 --> 41:24.023
the 1960's.

41:25.525 --> 41:27.944
- Ravi?
- Cue music. Ravi, music.

41:28.027 --> 41:28.903
[music starts]

41:28.987 --> 41:32.699
[George] Ravi, goddammit! Late! Late!
Ravi, late! Excuse me.

41:32.782 --> 41:36.369
As soon as he says "1960's,"
you come in fast with the groovy music.

41:36.452 --> 41:39.205
Ravi, you got to hit that cue
or he's gonna go bananas.

41:39.288 --> 41:41.833
No, no, I'll go banana bread on you,

41:41.916 --> 41:44.043
and it will be too dry to swallow.

41:45.294 --> 41:48.006
You ever fuck up
one of his monologues again,

41:48.089 --> 41:50.383
and I will choke you out, <i>Slumdog.</i>

41:52.802 --> 41:54.137
George!

41:55.930 --> 41:58.683
That is so chivalrous of you.

42:01.144 --> 42:03.563
You need to lose like seven pounds.

42:03.938 --> 42:05.231
[audience laugh]

42:07.233 --> 42:08.735
It's true.

42:09.193 --> 42:11.362
It's all the Tate's cookies, you know?

42:12.280 --> 42:13.740
They're so thin...

42:14.449 --> 42:18.619
You finish one sleeve and you're like,
"Well, there's just one sleeve left."

42:23.791 --> 42:27.086
Flash forward, the 1960's.

42:28.463 --> 42:32.133
I'm at Columbia University
as a trespasser.

42:33.926 --> 42:37.555
I was handing out flyers
for this cult I had joined, you know.

42:37.638 --> 42:40.516
Fun fact: I'm the only guy
to ever get kicked out of a cult

42:40.600 --> 42:42.477
for being too into it.

42:43.478 --> 42:44.937
But we were a great group.

42:45.021 --> 42:49.067
It was an LSD bicycle cult,
now known as Soul Cycle.

42:52.445 --> 42:54.781
The 1960's.

42:54.906 --> 42:55.907
[no music]

42:56.199 --> 42:57.575
[music cues in late]

43:01.496 --> 43:03.331
I'm a student at Columbia

43:03.414 --> 43:08.503
after an Army psychiatrist
deems me too violent for Vietnam.

43:08.961 --> 43:13.800
1969, millions watched Neil Armstrong
walk on the moon.

43:13.883 --> 43:15.635
I'll never forget where I was.

43:15.718 --> 43:19.764
On a sound stage in Queens
helping to fake the moon landing.

43:20.640 --> 43:22.600
But the '60s, you know?

43:22.975 --> 43:24.477
I remember one day,

43:24.560 --> 43:27.563
I'm walking through the Columbia quad.

43:27.647 --> 43:29.899
But the '60s, you know?

43:29.982 --> 43:33.694
I remember one day,
I'm walking through the Columbia quad.

43:34.070 --> 43:40.076
[both] And I see this really cool dude.

43:40.451 --> 43:44.288
- Oh, a peace, <i>Oh, hello.</i>
- '60s peace <i>Oh, hello </i> to you.

43:45.123 --> 43:46.457
Marijuana.

43:47.333 --> 43:50.962
I just heard about this really groovy
new apartment on 73rd Street.

43:51.045 --> 43:53.881
- You want to be room mates?
- I do want to be room mates, new friend.

43:53.965 --> 43:56.467
But I should warn you,
I may have to move out soon,

43:56.551 --> 43:59.720
'cause I'm engaged to this girl
who will not shut up.

44:00.721 --> 44:04.475
Well, I should warn you
that I am afraid of raccoons.

44:06.227 --> 44:08.646
These guys are crazy,
they got these little shoulders

44:08.729 --> 44:11.899
and that big belly
like a furry jar, you know?

44:11.983 --> 44:14.152
Watch out, raccoons,
they'll steal your food,

44:14.235 --> 44:16.612
but next thing you know,
they'll steal your heart.

44:16.696 --> 44:20.533
Raccoons said, "What are you?
A cat, or a fox, you neither?"

44:20.616 --> 44:22.827
- You're a raccoon.
- You're a raccoon, exactly.

44:22.910 --> 44:27.206
And then all of a sudden, they stand
up straight, that's weird, you know?

44:27.623 --> 44:30.710
They got those tails
that look like tie-dyed Swiffers.

44:30.793 --> 44:33.504
And have Swiffers even been invented yet?

44:33.963 --> 44:36.632
You got those human hands
that'll [pop] pop your eyeball out,

44:36.716 --> 44:38.009
eat it like a green grape.

44:38.092 --> 44:40.237
You ever heard a raccoon
eat a green grape? It's like...

44:40.261 --> 44:42.180
[grunty gnawing]

44:42.346 --> 44:45.516
And I bet in Australia,
they call them rubbish burglars.

44:45.975 --> 44:48.769
And they are so, so sexy.

44:49.353 --> 44:51.063
And another thing about raccoons...

44:51.147 --> 44:54.066
And we've lived together ever since.

44:55.151 --> 44:57.737
[applause]

45:01.824 --> 45:06.120
And then a letter comes in the mail
from some mailman.

45:06.662 --> 45:10.917
Because we don't have $2,500,
we're gonna lose our home.

45:11.000 --> 45:16.339
<i>♪ Oh, George, I'm so depressed
That we're moving out ♪</i>

45:16.422 --> 45:21.302
[harmonizing]

45:21.385 --> 45:23.596
OK, all right, that was interesting.

45:24.805 --> 45:27.016
I got a few big problems with that, Gil.

45:27.099 --> 45:30.311
First off, we do not have the rights
to Bill Joel's "Movin' Out."

45:30.937 --> 45:33.397
Right, that's why I yodeled it.

45:35.483 --> 45:37.860
That was way too big of a line reading.

45:37.944 --> 45:40.029
So don't do it again.

45:40.112 --> 45:42.782
Oh, yeah, sure, of course.

45:42.865 --> 45:43.950
[clears throat]

45:44.033 --> 45:47.453
Um, if we're doing feedback,
I-I was thinking,

45:47.536 --> 45:51.040
maybe you don't have to give
me notes during the play.

45:54.293 --> 45:55.294
Oh!

45:57.171 --> 45:59.507
- Oh, big kid, huh?
- No...

46:00.299 --> 46:03.803
Oh, big Gil rides a big wheel now, huh?

46:04.470 --> 46:06.472
No, no, no, hey, I like it.

46:06.806 --> 46:09.392
Uh, Let me ask you a question.

46:09.850 --> 46:14.397
You don't want to blow this
the way you did CBS, do you?

46:14.689 --> 46:16.232
[audience oohs]

46:16.315 --> 46:17.650
No.

46:18.693 --> 46:22.697
You think if you OD'd tomorrow
anyone would give a shit?

46:24.740 --> 46:27.535
You're God's born loser, you know that?

46:27.618 --> 46:30.538
You are God... No. No escape. Hey, no, no!

46:32.248 --> 46:33.290
[clears throat]

46:34.083 --> 46:36.836
Look, we both said
a lot of hurtful things, OK?

46:39.130 --> 46:42.383
But we got a nice audience,
so just please, cheer up, Gil.

46:42.466 --> 46:45.344
Do Mike Jackson, do King Pop.
Come on, Jackson.

46:46.762 --> 46:48.264
Yeah!

46:48.347 --> 46:49.432
[mimics camera clicks]

46:49.515 --> 46:53.102
- Mike Jackson.
- I want to hang a baby over a balcony.

46:54.020 --> 46:56.480
That was the funniest thing
that ever happened.

46:57.106 --> 46:58.899
There's only one way back, Mike.

46:58.983 --> 46:59.984
Yes.

47:00.818 --> 47:02.319
- Mike Jackson.
- Yeah.

47:02.403 --> 47:05.281
- You got good at that.
- I want to walk on the moon one day.

47:05.364 --> 47:06.991
Oh, that's sad. OK.

47:08.284 --> 47:11.871
Let's slip right back in, OK.
I don't think the audience knows.

47:12.955 --> 47:17.084
And then a letter comes in the mail
from some mailman.

47:17.168 --> 47:21.672
Because we don't have $2,500,
we're gonna lose our home.

47:21.756 --> 47:25.217
Oh, George, I'm so depressed
that we're moving out.

47:25.301 --> 47:26.552
So am I.

47:26.635 --> 47:27.928
But you know what?

47:28.012 --> 47:29.513
Let's not be depressed.

47:30.181 --> 47:33.517
If this is our last stay in New York,
let's have some fun.

47:34.143 --> 47:35.770
I was thinking.

47:35.853 --> 47:40.066
What if we went down
to the old WOLO Studios

47:40.149 --> 47:43.402
and taped a little episode
of <i>You Know What.</i>

47:43.486 --> 47:44.570
<i>You Know What?</i>

47:44.653 --> 47:48.491
Our game show that contestants
had to guess what you knew?

47:49.742 --> 47:52.787
That was such a vague and hard game show.

47:53.287 --> 47:57.541
'Cause we never narrowed it down
what it was, I could know.

47:57.625 --> 48:01.420
And the one time that guy guessed it,
I lied.

48:02.922 --> 48:07.384
No, fat feet,
I'm talking about our other show.

48:08.969 --> 48:12.807
[mood music plays]

48:16.560 --> 48:20.648
We take you now
to a big midtown New York City diner,

48:20.731 --> 48:23.234
where even ice cream tastes bad.

48:24.735 --> 48:27.029
Everyone there is ugly.

48:27.988 --> 48:32.201
Do you know what I mean?
Every single person...

48:32.827 --> 48:34.411
in their own way...

48:35.371 --> 48:36.997
is ugly.

48:37.414 --> 48:41.335
The menu is like, 19 pages long.

48:41.418 --> 48:45.714
And even though it's a diner,
it has stuff like lobster on it.

48:46.090 --> 48:51.470
And you're almost tempted to order it
to see just what would happen.

48:53.347 --> 48:55.766
We see beautiful Gil Stone.

48:55.850 --> 49:00.354
Because he's in a diner,
he eats like he's in a 70's movie.

49:07.486 --> 49:10.364
Hey, sweetheart,
bring me chicken cacciatore

49:10.447 --> 49:12.950
or another food
that doesn't exist anymore.

49:14.243 --> 49:17.371
Hey, darling, could I get a 1970s coffee,

49:17.454 --> 49:21.041
so watery and gray
and a gun next to it on the table.

49:21.959 --> 49:25.462
Hey, dear, bring me a half cantaloupe,
scoop cottage cheese,

49:25.546 --> 49:27.590
and a side steak Diane.

49:28.591 --> 49:30.634
Oh, shit, shit, we're live.

49:30.718 --> 49:31.886
[clears throat]

49:31.969 --> 49:35.472
[both] Oh, hello.

49:37.975 --> 49:40.352
[woman] <i>♪ Too Much Tuna ♪</i>

49:41.770 --> 49:43.105
[applause]

49:48.068 --> 49:50.738
<i>Oh, hello </i> and welcome to <i>Too Much Tuna</i>

49:50.821 --> 49:54.116
on WOLO Public Access.

49:54.617 --> 49:56.619
We welcome all of our viewers.

49:56.702 --> 49:59.413
Whether you're a cat,
alone in an apartment.

49:59.830 --> 50:02.041
Or a Honduran cleaning woman

50:02.124 --> 50:05.669
who is not sure
if she's allowed to change the channel.

50:07.338 --> 50:10.007
We welcome both of our viewers.

50:10.090 --> 50:12.009
<i>Too Much Tuna </i> is a prank show...

50:12.092 --> 50:15.804
- Eh, eh!
- Oh, shit. Can't say? Right. Take two.

50:15.888 --> 50:18.432
<i>- Too Much Tuna </i> is a talk show
- Yeah!

50:18.515 --> 50:20.309
- With no prank element.
- No, no.

50:20.392 --> 50:24.021
We merely interview the greatest
personalities in New York

50:24.104 --> 50:27.733
and they don't at all get a
huge fucking tuna comeuppance.

50:29.902 --> 50:32.947
This is our final episode
of <i>Too Much Tuna </i> ever

50:33.030 --> 50:36.450
as we're being forced
to leave our apartment in Manhattan.

50:36.533 --> 50:40.037
But for our final episode ever,
we have a very special guest.

50:40.120 --> 50:42.289
- We really do.
- He's a good guest.

50:42.373 --> 50:45.125
- He's a great guest. Sort of good get.
- It's a good get.

50:45.209 --> 50:48.337
He began as a writer
on the <i>Smothers Brothers' </i> comedy hour,

50:48.420 --> 50:50.839
and since then,
he's been one of the rising stars

50:50.923 --> 50:52.758
in the world of entertainment.

50:52.841 --> 50:55.052
Please welcome, Steve Martin.

50:55.803 --> 50:58.180
[applause]

51:05.354 --> 51:08.274
Bye, thanks for coming.
God bless you, thank you.

51:08.357 --> 51:11.110
Thank you. Thank you.

51:13.153 --> 51:14.238
Thank you.

51:24.790 --> 51:27.084
<i>♪ Too Much Tuna ♪</i>

51:27.167 --> 51:29.336
<i>♪ Welcome Steve to Too Much Tuna ♪</i>

51:29.420 --> 51:31.463
<i>♪ Welcome Steve to Too Much Tuna ♪</i>

51:32.339 --> 51:33.674
How long do I need to do that?

51:33.757 --> 51:34.758
[cheering]

51:34.883 --> 51:36.010
[Gil] Come on!

51:37.886 --> 51:39.013
[Steve] Thank you.

51:42.516 --> 51:43.517
Yeah, your belt?

51:43.600 --> 51:46.645
- I look great with this...
- Yeah, you do. You want to untie...

51:46.729 --> 51:49.940
I'm actually already wearing a mic
because I always wear a mic.

51:50.024 --> 51:53.736
- You never know. You want me to do this?
- Sure. Oh, yeah, go ahead.

51:53.819 --> 51:54.862
Let me get in there.

51:54.945 --> 51:57.364
- Like you dress.
- Yes. Oh, thank you.

51:57.448 --> 51:59.033
Yeah, I look like you now.

51:59.116 --> 52:00.743
- I don't want that button.
- No, OK.

52:00.826 --> 52:02.411
You want to leave it open?

52:02.494 --> 52:04.872
- You know, I've been around.
- Yes, OK.

52:04.955 --> 52:06.874
Oh, no. We know.

52:10.294 --> 52:12.046
- What a joy.
- Yeah.

52:12.129 --> 52:14.923
By the way, the sound is great.

52:15.507 --> 52:18.886
- Good, that's good to hear.
- Thank you for that measured compliment.

52:21.263 --> 52:25.184
Let's put it this way,
I have great hopes from here on out.

52:25.267 --> 52:26.727
Oh, that's so nice.

52:26.810 --> 52:29.772
You yourself are a playwright
of some great esteem.

52:29.855 --> 52:31.231
Well, thank you very much.

52:31.315 --> 52:33.859
- But I think you've nailed it.
- Thank you.

52:33.942 --> 52:37.237
- You nailed the essence of playwriting.
- Thank you.

52:37.321 --> 52:39.448
By the way, you know
what Mike Nichols told me once.

52:39.531 --> 52:42.201
- He said, there was the...
- Oh, you drop something.

52:44.953 --> 52:48.332
Jesus Christ.
Two minutes in to the interview.

52:50.084 --> 52:52.336
- Not that Mike Nichols.
- Oh, all right.

52:53.045 --> 52:58.300
He told me that RKO Pictures
had a philosophy that if...

52:58.384 --> 53:02.179
In their movies, when the phone rang,
if the news was sad,

